SA2) were cross-linked by a third strand (L3) with a base sequence complementary to both side-branch DNA strands. The stiffness of these gels can be dynamically increased by introducing additional cross-links and can be modulated over a wide range by varying the choice of base sequence or by varying the length and structure of the DNA cross-links. In addition, the stiffness can also be reduced by including extra nucleotides in the cross-linker (F1) to form a toehold. Then by introducing a fourth strand (CF1), which is fully complementary to the crosslinking strand, the gel can be disassembled. These gels have been shown to be biocompatible and were used to examine the cellular responses of spinal cord neurons to substrate stiffness.7 Chippada et al.1 used a magnetic manipulator to observe the displacement of nonspherical magnetic inclusions in the form of nickel needles of 10 1 1 mm size. Figure 1 shows a schematic of the manipulator that consists of four electromagnets placed at the four corners of a 12.5 12.5 cm square iron frame. By changing the values of the magnetic field at the four poles of the manipulator, the force acting on the microneedles was regulated. Knowing the force acting on the needles and the displacement of the needles, the stiffness (k = F/d) of the hydrogels was determined. In the present study,
