III. MATERIALS AND METHODS
A. PAAM gel preparation
PAAM gels were prepared using the protocol described in Chippada et al.1 In short, microneedles fabricated at NJNC (New Jersey Nanotechnology Consortium LLC, New Providence, NJ, a wholly owned subsidiary of Alcatel-Lucent) were dissolved in dH2O and added to a mixture of acrylamide/bis-acrylamide stock solution (40% w/v, Sigma-Aldrich, St. Louis, MO). Polymerization is initiated by adding 2% of total volume of 5% ammonium persulfate, and 2% of total volume of N,N,N0,N0-tetramethylethylene-diamine (TEMED) at 1:5 dilution is used as a catalyst to speed up the gel formation. Then 52 mL of this solution was quickly transferred to a specially made 8.4 mm well where the gel formed. Three different concentrations (namely 3%, 4%, and 5%) of PAAM gels were prepared by altering the amount of acrylamide/bis-acrylamide stock solutions that were added in each case.
B. DNA gel preparation
DNA base sequences, optimized to minimize secondary structure formation, were obtained from Integrated DNA Technologies (Coralville, IA). Acrydite (Matrix Technologies, Hudson, NH) modification was added to the 50 end of the SA1 and SA2 strands to allow for
copolymerization with acrylamide. The sequences for the SA1, SA2, and the cross-linker L3 are as shown in Table I. The gel is called a 14-14-40 DNA hydrogel, nomenclatured after the number of bases in SA1, SA2, and L3 respectively. SA1 and SA2 stock solutions were prepared from the DNA strands, in TE buffer containing microneedles. After bubbling dry nitrogen for 2 min, 5% ammonium persulfate was added to initiate the polymerization and TEMED was used as a catalyst. Nitrogen was again bubbled to complete the polymerization of the individual stock solutions as described in Lin et al.14 40% cross-linked DNA gels were prepared in 8.4 mm wells, by adding 20 mL of SA1 stock solution, 20 mL of SA2 stock solution, and 12 mL of 40% cross-linker. After the 40% cross-linked gels were tested in both translation and rotation, 10% additional cross-linker was added to increase the total percentage of cross-linker in the gels to 50%. These gels were tested in a similar manner, and the process is then repeated for 60% cross-linked gels.
C. Four-magnet manipulator testing protocol
The space between the four poles of the manipulator was probed using a preprogrammed analog Hall sensor (Sensor Solutions Corp., Steamboat Springs, CO) attached to a micropositioning stage. The magnetic field at various locations in the space was measured for various combinations of the field strengths at the poles. Thus, a complete map of the space was obtained from which the strength and gradient of magnetic field at any location could be determined by extrapolation from the measured points. 52 mL of either the PAAM gel or the DNA gel was cast in a 8.4 mm well and placed in the space between the four poles of the magnet manipulator. The manipulator was mounted on an Olympus BX51 microscope with a 50 objective lens. A gradient magnetic field was generated by keeping the magnetic field at the attracting pole at a larger value, while maintaining the magnetic field at the remaining poles at a smaller value. Images of the motion of the microneedles under the influence of this external magnetic field were taken using a Matrix Vision Bluefox USB camera with a 1600 1200 pixel sensor and a 12 mm lens. Using the initial image as a reference, the displacement of the needles was evaluated as the magnetic field at the poles was increased.
