IV. RESULTS
A. Calibration constant
Figure 3 shows a representative set of data for the rheological testing of 3% PAAM gels, as frequency is varied between 0 and 10 Hz. The shear or storage modu
lus increased gradually with frequency and then dropped off at higher frequencies. Examination of the gels revealed that they ruptured at higher frequencies, and this could be the reason for the decrease in modulus. The average shear modulus of these gels was found to be equal to 354 6 Pa. When the same gel was tested in the four-magnet setup, application of a gradient field of 5.82 G/mm displaced the microneedle by 2.43 mm. Four such gels were tested, and using this information in Eq. (7), the average value of the calibration constant (mp) was determined to be 2.0 10 16 N-m/G. This value of mp is used to calculate the force and torque in all the remaining microneedle experiments.
B. Mechanical properties of PAAM gels
At each of three different concentrations (3%, 4%, and 5%), four samples of PAAM gels were prepared with microneedles embedded in them and tested in the fourmagnet setup. In each sample, two needles at different locations were isolated and either a gradient magnetic field or a uniform magnetic field was applied. Figures 4(a) and 4(b) show the deflection and the rotation of the needles under the influence of these fields, respectively. In the gradient magnetic field, the needle displaces toward the left by a distance represented by d. Similarly, under the influence of the torque field, the needle rotates about its center by an angle y. The results of the forcedisplacement and torque-rotation experiments for 3%, 4%, and 5% PAAM gels are presented in Table II. The samples are labeled from 1 to 4, while A and B represent two needles in the same sample. As the percentage of cross-linker increases from 3% to 5%, the value of F/d also increases. This means that for the same force the needle displaces by a smaller amount in the gel. Similarly, the value of G/y also increases with increase in concentration, indicating that for the same amount of torque, the needle rotates by a smaller amount. The shear modulus and elastic modulus also increase with increasing concentration. The shear modulus was found to be equal to 309.4 37.4 Pa for the 3% PAAM gel, 495.7 65.3 Pa for the 4% PAAM gels, and 1890.4 282.1 Pa for the 5% PAAM gels. The average Young’s moduli for
