An interesting aspect of Poisson’s ratio of hydrogels is its dependence on the degree of swelling of the hydrogel. Because swelling is inversely related to the cross-linker concentration, it is expected that at higher cross-linker concentration, Poisson’s ratio will also be higher.16,33,34 A comparison of the Poisson’s ratio with respect to the bis-cross-linker concentration is performed for PAAM gels in Fig. 10. It can be observed that between 3% and 4% gels, there is no appreciable change in the Poisson’s ratio. However, between 4% and 5% there is a significant increase in Poisson’s ratio. This could be attributed to difference in increase of stiffness of these gels: 890.6 to 1414.2 Pa from 3% to 4% gels, while it is 1414.2 to 5668.2 Pa from 4% to 5% gels. Also, it should be noted that the methodology used in the current study is independent of the medium, and thus the capabilities can be useful for the investigation of the local mechanical properties of various soft materials at the micron scale. The calibration constant obtained from Eq. (7) is dependent on the material and shape of the inclusion. Thus mp must be determined, prior to using the needles in the magnet setup. Also, it should be noted that the present method cannot completely characterize an anisotropic gel or material. To demonstrate that, one would have to be able to map out how the stiffness of the gel depends on the direction of the applied force and the
direction of the applied torque for any arbitrary direction. Among other things, it would require that we be able to displace the inclusion along the z axis as well as the x and y axis, which is beyond the scope of the present study. Also in the anisotropic case G, E, and n are no longer adequate to describe the mechanical properties of the material, these must, instead be replaced by tensor quantities.
VI. CONCLUSIONS
The stiffness of the substrate plays an important role in the behavior of cells. In most of the research done to date, hydrogels were considered to be incompressible and their Poisson’s ratio was assumed to be equal to one-half. This may not be true in all cases especially for gels that swell when placed in a buffer solution or media. To characterize the stiffness accurately, a method by which the Young’s modulus, shear modulus, and Poisson’s ration of the gels can be determined simultaneously was presented. Measurements of the two independent quantities F/d and G/y were made on two different gels, namely bis-acrylamide and DNA cross-linked gels to obtain the Young’s modulus, shear modulus, and Poisson’s ratio. The method presented is a nonintrusive technique that allows us to determine the properties of inhomogeneous materials at the 10 mm scale. This gives us a better understanding of the hydrogels and would enhance the study of the behavior of cells on these substrates.
